         <abstract>
            <p>A very simple rigorous procedure is derived for computing the Brouwer degree in $R^2$, a generalization of the zero-counting integral $\oint f'(z)dz/f(z)$, for functions which are Lipschitz continuous on a piecewise linear path of integration, using only computed or observed values of $f(z)$, a bound for the error in them, and a bound for the Lipschitz constant. It is used to locate zeros and to test the numerical significance of zeros found by other methods.</p>
          </abstract>
